		<div class="post" id="post-3562906">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,3562906)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-3562906">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/chubert" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(502908); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=502908&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205836" alt="Chubert" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=502908)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/chubert" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(502908); return false;" >Chubert</a></span> <span class="odate time_1501640271 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">02 Aug 2017 02:17</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3562906">
									

<p>Going to comment on T-Minus and T-Plus at the same time.</p>
<p>I was definitely not a fan of the way the action went down in T-Plus, because the majority of it is Shiva gunning down demon goons-for a tale that's 7k words long, I need some more. Additionally, part of the reason I felt frustrated was that you set up this GoI menage a trois in T-Minus, but decide not to go for it in this tale-I understand if you're planning on reintroducing it later on this series, but that's still 7k words of Shiva-as-Doomguy. I have zero reason to care about demon-gibbing or the extremely-detailed means by which it happens, because as far as I can tell the demons themselves have zero motivation. If you had went for the GoI conflict, I think you could have hooked me into the action a lot more effectively by exploring the contrasts in GoI motivations/approaches to the mission (kinda like you did in T-Minus).</p>
<p>I think pacing is also not working in your favor here. Most of the actions Shiva takes over the course of the tale do not matter: it is finding tunnels, pushing trains, plugging in fuses, using magitek-all stuff that is super routine, and yet is described, along with Shiva moving from Point A to Point B, in inordinate detail.</p>
<p>Moving onto character in the piece, it bugs me that I can so neatly separate character from action. If I had only read Shiva's narration and not read any of the action pieces, I would've gotten 100% of Shiva's character arc, which is problematic because it means that Shiva's character development and the action are completely independent.</p>
<p>I think the strongest thing working for me in the piece so far is the character of Shiva. I think the character arc was a bit poorly paced as well, with several story beats (Shiva discovers that something is wrong with itself, Shiva wonders why it didn't tell a tech, Shiva learns that it is a pacifist) reiterated a couple times before the story moves on to the next one. But I like the arc itself-it's a bit tropey as far as AI stories come, but I liked the innocent, inquisitive tone that Shiva adopts. The section when it's ruminating on the nature of love was definitely the high point of the tale series for me. What's noteworthy is that you completely limit yourself to Shiva's internal narration when describing its character arc, and the novelty of the internal conversation can only take you so far. I think if you want a tale as long as this is, I would've liked it more if there was a lot less demon-gibbing and a lot more development on Shiva's arc.</p>

							</div>

								
					
